{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478180"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:10:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17003"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17003"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.23,0.07,0.12,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68196"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9693"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53653"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1286"},{"type":"tags","id":"2130"},{"type":"tags","id":"2143"},{"type":"tags","id":"6020"},{"type":"tags","id":"6029"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39720"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68196"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department after falling onto his outstretched hand while playing at the park one hour ago. He has pain and swelling in his right wrist. He has no other injuries. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is mild swelling and tenderness over the distal radius. He has full range of movement of his fingers and normal sensation. His radial pulse is normal. X-rays show a buckle fracture of the distal radius with dorsal cortical deformity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Buddy strapping","Removable splint","Surgical fixation","Above-elbow plaster cast","Below-elbow plaster cast"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a typical buckle (torus) fracture of the distal radius, which is one of the most common paediatric fractures. These injuries occur when compressive forces cause buckling of the cortex on one side of the bone, typically after a fall onto an outstretched hand.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemovable splint\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for buckle fractures. Recent evidence shows that removable splints are as effective as plaster casts, with the added benefits of improved function, easier hygiene, and greater convenience. The splint can be removed for bathing and gentle range of motion exercises, and can be discontinued when the child is comfortable (typically 3-4 weeks).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBelow-elbow plaster cast\u003C/strong\u003E was traditionally used but is unnecessarily restrictive for these stable injuries. Studies have shown no difference in outcomes between casting and removable splints, while splints have better patient satisfaction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbove-elbow plaster cast\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly restrictive and inappropriate for this stable distal radius fracture. Above-elbow immobilisation is typically reserved for more proximal or unstable forearm fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical fixation\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for buckle fractures as they are inherently stable injuries with excellent healing potential in children. Surgery would expose the child to unnecessary risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBuddy strapping\u003C/strong\u003E alone provides insufficient support for a buckle fracture of the radius. While it might be appropriate for certain finger injuries, it would not provide adequate immobilisation for this injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParents should be counselled that routine follow-up x-rays are not necessary unless there are concerns about healing or persistent symptoms. The prognosis is excellent with complete healing expected within 4-6 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buckle (torus) fractures of the distal radius are stable injuries that can be safely managed with a removable splint.","Removable splints in paediatric buckle fractures improve function, are more convenient, and have equal outcomes to cast immobilisation.","Follow-up imaging is not routinely required for uncomplicated buckle fractures."],"references":["Ben-Yakov M, Boutis K. Buckle fractures of the distal radius in children. CMAJ. 2016 Apr 19;188(7):527. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.151239. Epub 2016 Mar 14. PMID: 26976961; PMCID: PMC4835283."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53653"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17003"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53653"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:36:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:37:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9693"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68196"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"at